/*
Path analysis:
There are two observable execution outcomes after the loop.

1. The loop finds the n-th value in [l, r] such that i % a != 0.
   On each iteration, count is incremented exactly when the current i is not divisible by a.
   If after this increment count == n, the function returns the current i immediately.
   In this path, the returned value is the first index i in the loop range for which the number of prior non-multiples of a reaches n.

2. The loop completes without ever reaching count == n.
   In this path, the function returns -1.

The function only modifies local variables count and i, and has no caller-visible side effects.
*/

int foo348(int a, int n, int l, int r) {

        int count = 0;
        
        /*@
          loop invariant l <= i;
          loop invariant 0 <= count;
          loop invariant count <= i - l;
          loop assigns i, count;
        */
        for (int i = l; i <= r; i++) {
            if (i % a != 0) {
                count++;
            }
            if (count == n) {
                return i;
            }
        }
            
        return -1;
}

